  "response_text": "The aggregated simulation output reveals a consistent and statistically significant upward trend in the cumulative count of whole milk selections across the 33 time steps. The metric initiates at 0.0000 at index 0 and concludes at 2194.5667 at index 32, with a mean value of 1130.8818 and a standard deviation of 654.6927. Statistical testing via the rolling Mann-Kendall method confirms an increasing trend across all six analyzed windows (indices 0-4 through 25-29), with a tau of 1.000 and a p-value of 0.027 for each segment. While the direction remains strictly positive, the rate of growth shows a gradual deceleration, with the slope declining from 70.808 in the earliest period to 64.067 in the final period.\n\nWithin the context of the consumer behavior model spanning 1974 to 2005, this trajectory reflects the enduring influence of established habits despite shifting social and health norms. The parameter incumbent-initial-habit is set to 10.0, well above the habit-threshold of 2.0, ensuring that agents maintain a strong predisposition toward the incumbent whole milk product throughout the simulation. This high baseline habit strength explains the substantial accumulation of choice events, even as parameters like alt-health-mean-initial (1.69) and social-susceptibility (0.2) introduce pressures to switch to skimmed or semi-skimmed alternatives. The slight reduction in the slope over time suggests that while the total volume of whole milk choices grows with the passage of time, the frequency per step may be moderating, aligning with the broader model goal of replicating the historical transition toward lower fat milk varieties."
}

